training_organizations.name: Hawaii DHS – Child Welfare Services Staff Development
training_organizations.description: The Hawaii Department of Human Services runs the child abuse reporting hotline and investigations (statewide unit, given Hawaii has a unified state system). No indication of these being outsourced. Reunification & Foster Care Placement: Hawaii contracts with some nonprofit providers for family support and reunification services (e.g. parenting classes, visitation programs) and for recruiting foster homes (such as Catholic Charities helping with foster parent licensing). Core foster care placements and case management are done by state DHS social workers. No recent vendor contract shifts were found in sources; Hawaii’s system remains mostly state-operated with provider partnerships.

training_organizations.name: Catholic Charities Hawaii
training_organizations.description: A nonprofit social service agency that partners with Hawaii’s child welfare system to support foster care. Catholic Charities Hawaii helps recruit and train foster parents and assists with licensing. They also provide prevention services and help place children with kin or foster families, playing a key role in expanding foster home capacity:contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}.

policies.Def_Subtype_Abuse: Physical abuse includes failure to thrive and shaken baby syndrome (subdural hematoma)
policies.Def_Subtype_Neglect: Neglect includes inadequate clothing, inadequate shelter, malnourishment, medical neglect, and inability to meet parent responsibilities

policies.ReportInfo_OtherSpecify: Race, ethnicity, employment, marital status (unspecified which party this information pertains to); If there are others who are aware of the harm; Support system for family
policies.ScreenInfo_OtherSpecify: Names and ages of other persons who live with the child and their relationship to the child if known; Name and address of child's parents or persons responsible for child; Location and time of incident; Any other information the reporter believes might be helpful to the investigation of child abuse and neglect
policies.DefAge_VaryByTypeSpecify: Abandonment applies to children who are 3 or younger
policies.DefPerp_VaryByTypeSpecify: For physical abuse and neglect, the perpetrator is any person who is a family member, household member, or person responsible for child; For trafficking, the perpetrator is any person
policies.InvestQual_ExperienceSpecify: 1.5 years of specialized experience and 1 year of protective services experience; Bachelor's degree in social work may be substituted for 6 months of specialized experience; Master's degree in social work or related field may be substituted for 1.5 years of specialized experience, provided that coursework focused on preparation for direct services work and human condition; Excess protective services experience may be substituted for specialized experience on a month-for-month basis
policies.ScreenReq_OtherCases_Specify: For immediate safety concerns; Questionable reports where there has been no disclosure of maltreatment; Report is 'red flag' behavior by the child
policies.AntiDiscrim_Staff_VarySpecify: (1) Race, gender identity or expression, sexual orientation, disability, national origin, color, ancestry, pregnancy, and parenting status are specified for specified for staff from child welfare agency, contracted child welfare provider organizations, and volunteers; (2) Religion is specified for staff from child welfare agency; (3) Sex and immigration are specified for volunteers

policies.AltResp_EligibilityMaltreatment: Only certain types of maltreatment are eligible
policies.AltResp_EligibilityRiskToolSpec: Child Welfare Services Intake Assessment Tool or Child Safety Assessment and Child Strengths and Risks Assessment
